review_blob: 2004 bottling.  Wonderful aroma dominated by the hops.  Nice dark copper red/brown color.  Strong malt flavor, with a chocolate hint.  Excellent hops flavor and aftertaste.  Alcohol has a noticably warm feel.  An annual favorite in my house.

Beautiful dark brown color with a reddish tint.  The roasted malts come through strongly with a chocolate and nutty flavor.  The head lasts a good while.  Not heavy tasting, a great porter for the price.
A light cloudy color, with a strong wheat and yeast taste.  A nice sediment of yeast in the bottle, something I like.  An excellent Hefe for the money.
Nice copper color.  Doesnt taste like it has 7.7% alcohol.  Quite sweet tasting with the roasted malt coming through well.  Medium carbonation and a light pleasing aroma.  A good Oktoberfest.

Coppery brown color, decent light brown/tan head.  Being an IPA, it has a nice hoppy taste, not as well hopped as others I,ve tried, but very satisfactory.  The malts are OK but they dont last long.  Aftertaste is what I expected.  All in all a decent beer.

An excellent effort from New Ulm!  Wonderful dark amber color and Full lacey head.  The hops are very noticable from the first sip.  The malt is there too, but the hops remain throughout.  A great bitter taste, what I like in an ale such as this.  Could have called it an IPA.   My favorite from Schells.

Like the commercial deScription says, Schells Dark does not have all the flavor and heaviness.  That doesnt mean its flavorless, but it is much light than one would expect from a dark beer, though still it tasted OK.  The color is more red than brown, but still attractive.  Typical light head when poured.  A beer to break in someone whos been raised on supermarket beers.
A good golden beer with a light zest.  The wheat is evident, with a fruity aftertaste.  Not a heavy drink, but refreshing.
Orange color, looked pretty nice.   Taste was a little thin, bitterness is noted in the aftertaste.  Not a bad beer to drink with friends.  Part of a sampler pack.
